canonical:
  title: 謝乞請留李相表
  author: 無名氏
  language: lzh
  text: 宸眷悉深曲從敷奏睿恩偏重冞激兢惶省循以還感佩無已竊念弊服邈處荒陬常切嚮風欽仰皇猷之彌謹每當傳命必因象譯而乃通第緣師授之不明而致語音之失正幸玆邊戎之俘虜本是上國之編氓未敢便留迺煩陳請何圖聖神之憐察特加褒崇而允兪玆蓋伏遇俯矜慕義之誠益廣同文之化遂令賤品獲被殊私臣謹當期用夏而變夷奉揚聲敎願以小而事大恒祝康寧
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 謝乞請留李相表
  author: 無名氏
  language: lzh
  text: 宸眷悉深。曲從敷奏。睿恩偏重。冞激兢惶。省循以還。感佩無已。竊念弊服。邈處荒陬。常切嚮風。欽仰皇猷之彌謹。每當傳命。必因象譯而乃通。第緣師授之不明。而致語音之失正。幸玆邊戎之俘虜。本是上國之編氓。未敢便留。迺煩陳請。何圖聖神之憐察。特加褒崇而允兪。玆蓋伏遇俯矜慕義之誠。益廣同文之化。遂令賤品。獲被殊私。臣謹當期用夏而變夷。奉揚聲敎。願以小而事大。恒祝康寧。
korean:
  title: 이상을 머물기를 요청하고 사례하는 글
  author: 무명씨
  language: kor
  text: 황제의 돌보심이 깊으시어 아뢰는 것을 곡진하게 들어주시니, 은혜가 치우치게 무거움에 더욱 황공하여 제 몸을 살펴보매 감격하기를 마지않습니다.생각건대, 소국이 멀리 한 모퉁이에 거처하여, 언제나 간절히 풍화(風化)를 입어, 공경히 황제의 법도를 사모하기를 더욱 삼갑니다. 매양 명을 전달할 때에는 반드시 역관으로 통하였습니다. 다만 역어(譯語)를 전수받음이 밝지 못하기 때문에, 어음(語音)이 바름을 잃게 되었더니, 다행히 이제 변방의 포로가 본시 상국(上國)의 백성이므로, 감히 함부로 머물러 두지 못하고 번거롭게 아뢰어 청하였더니, 어찌 성신(聖神)께서 어여삐 여기시어 특별히 포장을 더하여 윤허할 줄 생각하였겠습니까. 이것은 대개 사모하는 정성을 가상히 여기어 더욱 동문(同文)의 교화를 넓혀서, 드디어 천한 몸으로 하여금 특수한 은혜를 입게 하심을 만난 것입니다.신은 삼가 마땅히 중화(中華)를 써서 이속(夷俗)을 변혁하여 교화를 받들어 선양(宣揚)하고, 소국으로서 대국을 섬겨서 언제나 강녕하시기를 빌겠습니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0410_010_0340&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Memorial of Gratitude for Permission to Retain the Minister Lee
  author: Anonymous
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Imperial Majesty's benevolence runs deep, and you have graciously received my humble petition. Your sage favor has fallen upon us with particular generosity, which fills me with trembling awe. Upon reflection on my humble station, my gratitude knows no bounds.

    I consider that our small realm dwells in a distant corner, forever yearning to receive the transforming influence of your civilizing grace, and ever more earnestly do we revere the illustrious way of the Emperor. When imperial commands are transmitted, they must necessarily pass through our interpreters. Yet because the teaching of translation has been imperfect, the sounds of our speech have lost their proper form.

    Fortunately, this captive from the frontier lands was originally a subject of your great realm. We dared not presume to retain him without permission, and so humbly submitted this request. How could we have imagined that Your Sage Majesty would look upon us with such compassion, granting us special honor and approval?

    This is truly an encounter with your gracious regard for our sincere admiration, whereby you extend further the civilization of shared written characters. Thus does this humble realm receive such extraordinary favor.

    Your servant shall diligently employ the ways of the Middle Kingdom to transform our barbarous customs, upholding and proclaiming your teachings. As a small state in service to the great, we forever pray for your eternal peace and prosperity.
  footnotes:
    - This memorial appears to be from a tributary state requesting permission to retain a native-born minister who had been captured. The text reflects the formal diplomatic language used between tributary states and the Chinese imperial court during the medieval period.
    - The phrase 'civilization of shared written characters' (同文) refers to the Sino-centric cultural sphere where Classical Chinese was used as the language of administration and scholarship.
    - The contrast between the 'Middle Kingdom' (中華) and 'barbarous customs' (夷俗) reflects the hierarchical worldview of East Asian tributary relations of this period.
